at grapples with issues of family, love, abandonment, and ultimately, forgiveness and reconciliation. It is also a spellbinding detective story—steeped in racial politics and the troubled history of two continents—of one man's search for the truth behind the enigmas of his, and his mother's, lives.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAfrican AmericansvBiography. 0aAfrican AmericansxCivil rightszSouthern StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aApartheidzSouth Africa. 0aCivil rights movementszSouthern StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aGeography. 0aHistory. 0aHouze, David. 0aSiblings. 7aHISTORY / Social History.2bisacsh  aabandonment.  aafrica.  aafrican american.  aamerican south.  aapartheid.  aautobiography.  abiography.  ablack.  acivil rights.  acolonialism.  adiscrimination.  aex pat.  aexpatriate.  afamily.  aforgiveness.  ahistory.  aidentity.  aimmigration.  aimperialism.  alost family.  alost siblings.  amemoir.  amississippi.  anonfiction.  apersonal narrative.  apolitical history.  aprejudice.  arace.  aracial politics.  aracism.  areconciliation.  arefugee.  aself discovery.  asisters.  asocial history.  asocial issues.  asouth africa.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052024398940uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052093174940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520931749423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520931749/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY